1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:07,000
 !!!!

2
00:00:07,000 --> 00:00:08,000
 So thank you.

3
00:00:08,000 --> 00:00:15,000
 So now we have the last session of this admin conference.

4
00:00:15,000 --> 00:00:26,000
 Which is probably not the least important topic, which is the financial aspect of this.

5
00:00:26,000 --> 00:00:33,000
 So I am the chair of this panel and I have a couple of slides on my country, Iceland,on the current situation.

6
00:00:33,000 --> 00:00:45,000
 Which I think that fit very neatly with the discussion previously on the labour market.

7
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:49,000
 So this is the policy rate in Iceland.

8
00:00:49,000 --> 00:00:58,000
 And in fact, just before I came to this conference on Wednesday,we raised the policy rate by 125 persons.

9
00:00:58,000 --> 00:01:01,000
 And this is a policy response.

10
00:01:01,000 --> 00:01:06,000
 We are using one policy to basically to cool on overheating economy.

11
00:01:06,000 --> 00:01:13,000
 As you can see inflation in most of the countries is beginning to slide.

12
00:01:13,000 --> 00:01:18,000
 But it's starting to rise in our country.

13
00:01:18,000 --> 00:01:21,000
 Or not going down.

14
00:01:21,000 --> 00:01:25,000
 Inflation in Iceland is now about 9.5%.

15
00:01:25,000 --> 00:01:29,000
 And has been on this level now for like six months.

16
00:01:29,000 --> 00:01:36,000
 One of the main problems is the labour market.

17
00:01:36,000 --> 00:01:47,000
 Because we have seen Iceland is probably the only country in Europe where the people have not taken a real wage cut.

18
00:01:47,000 --> 00:01:52,000
 People's nominal wage increases have kept up with inflation.

19
00:01:52,000 --> 00:02:03,000
 And what we are about to see might be the beginning of an wage inflation spiral.

20
00:02:03,000 --> 00:02:08,000
 And that is one of the reasons for why we decided to take this very drastic message.

21
00:02:08,000 --> 00:02:21,000
 And this comes on top of a situation that we have an economy that is growing very rapidly.

22
00:02:21,000 --> 00:02:34,000
 And the turn of events in the world in the past one or two years has actually been a very positive supply shock for us.

23
00:02:34,000 --> 00:02:39,000
 First of all, the price of our exports are increasing.

24
00:02:39,000 --> 00:02:44,000
 Our main exports are actually aluminum, fish.

25
00:02:44,000 --> 00:02:47,000
 And then the tourism sector is booming.

26
00:02:47,000 --> 00:02:53,000
 And especially visitors from the US.

27
00:02:53,000 --> 00:03:00,000
 But it's more than that because what has basically happened is that the value of our resources has increased.

28
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:04,000
 Because Iceland is mostly carbon free.

29
00:03:04,000 --> 00:03:09,000
 Ninety percent of our households use thermal energy with heating.

30
00:03:09,000 --> 00:03:19,000
 So what we are now seeing is an increased interest in investment in our country.

31
00:03:19,000 --> 00:03:22,000
 And in various aspects.

32
00:03:22,000 --> 00:03:28,000
 But this is a slide just telling about the population increase.

33
00:03:28,000 --> 00:03:31,000
 Iceland is a very young population.

34
00:03:31,000 --> 00:03:34,000
 The population growth has been very rapid by natural causes.

35
00:03:34,000 --> 00:03:40,000
 Icelandic women tend to have many kids compared with what is in Europe.

36
00:03:40,000 --> 00:03:44,000
 But also we have seen a huge inflow of labor.

37
00:03:44,000 --> 00:03:48,000
 We are part of the European economic area.

38
00:03:48,000 --> 00:03:57,000
 And we have seen -- I mean all of Western Europe has seen an influx of foreign labor.

39
00:03:57,000 --> 00:04:00,000
 But Iceland is basically exceptional.

40
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:03,000
 Population is growing very rapidly.

41
00:04:03,000 --> 00:04:10,000
 And this is our natural growth path.

42
00:04:10,000 --> 00:04:15,000
 We have a much higher rate of long-term growth.

43
00:04:15,000 --> 00:04:19,000
 And growth last year was about six, seven percent real.

44
00:04:19,000 --> 00:04:24,000
 And we project it to be five percent this year.

45
00:04:24,000 --> 00:04:37,000
 And what we've seen -- also see that -- I think there was this phrase yesterday by -- I think that --

46
00:04:37,000 --> 00:04:42,000
 a quote in Max Fritz that we imported labor.

47
00:04:42,000 --> 00:04:44,000
 But what we got was people.

48
00:04:44,000 --> 00:04:50,000
 Because the foreign workers, they need a place to stay.

49
00:04:50,000 --> 00:05:00,000
 And increasingly people, foreign workers that come to a country, they increasingly are buying houses.

50
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:04,000
 And want to stay in a country.

51
00:05:04,000 --> 00:05:07,000
 And that is creating a huge housing shortage.

52
00:05:07,000 --> 00:05:11,000
 And, you know, rising housing prices.

53
00:05:11,000 --> 00:05:18,000
 And now currently about 20, 25 percent of our labor force is foreign born.

54
00:05:18,000 --> 00:05:23,000
 And so far this has been going quite well.

55
00:05:23,000 --> 00:05:26,000
 There hasn't -- haven't been any serious problems.

56
00:05:26,000 --> 00:05:32,000
 Well, xenophobia or anything like that.

57
00:05:32,000 --> 00:05:40,000
 We -- most of the people that we -- that are in our country are just --

58
00:05:40,000 --> 00:05:49,000
 -- it is basically recognized in Iceland that these foreign workers are -- basically have a positive impact on our economy.

59
00:05:49,000 --> 00:05:56,000
 After the financial crisis, we -- as I will tell you about, we have been quite focused on keeping leverage down.

60
00:05:56,000 --> 00:06:05,000
 Because we got into this financial bubble, a huge inflow of foreign capital, which then ended in a crisis.

61
00:06:05,000 --> 00:06:14,000
 So as I will show you, we have been following a policy of very strict macroprudential measures to keep leverage down.

62
00:06:14,000 --> 00:06:20,000
 Also to keep the foreign exposure of the economy at a minimum.

63
00:06:20,000 --> 00:06:32,000
 And just to recap, we had -- in 2008, we had a financial crisis, systematic banking collapse.

64
00:06:32,000 --> 00:06:47,000
 And I would like to quote Giovanni in a pun yesterday, saying that there are financial stabilizers if the system is closed.

65
00:06:47,000 --> 00:06:56,000
 Of course, if the -- if the -- if the -- if the system is open, and money is trying to flee out to the country, it becomes a disaster.

66
00:06:56,000 --> 00:07:02,000
 As it -- as it was to the -- so -- so in order to -- to take control over financial system, we did two things.

67
00:07:02,000 --> 00:07:08,000
 Capital controls and also complete deposit insurance.

68
00:07:08,000 --> 00:07:12,000
 Which basically gave us time to reorganize the banking sector.

69
00:07:12,000 --> 00:07:17,000
 And which was basically cut down -- you had the banking system that was ten times our output.

70
00:07:17,000 --> 00:07:23,000
 And basically, we took force mature rights to cut the banks in two parts.

71
00:07:23,000 --> 00:07:28,000
 Foreign part that was put into liquidation and the domestic part that was recapitalized.

72
00:07:28,000 --> 00:07:37,000
 And behind capital controls, we basically built a new financial system.

73
00:07:37,000 --> 00:07:39,000
 The controls were basically abolished.

74
00:07:39,000 --> 00:07:50,000
 And I would like to mention that the -- we were in a -- the capital controls, they were operated with -- within the care of the IMF.

75
00:07:50,000 --> 00:07:59,000
 And the leader of the IMF contingent in Iceland is here, Paul Thomson.

76
00:07:59,000 --> 00:08:02,000
 He was actually sent to Iceland in 2008.

77
00:08:02,000 --> 00:08:12,000
 And it's basically the Iceland case also proved to be kind of a policy change with the IMF.

78
00:08:12,000 --> 00:08:16,000
 So -- so what have we done since?

79
00:08:16,000 --> 00:08:25,000
 First of all, it was very clear that we had to integrate and distribute responsibility for monetary policy, finance stability, and supervision.

80
00:08:25,000 --> 00:08:30,000
 Which basically means giving it to the central bank.

81
00:08:30,000 --> 00:08:38,000
 And so the central bank, which I represent, has basically a full mandate in financial stability, supervision, and monetary policy.

82
00:08:38,000 --> 00:08:44,000
 So if something goes wrong, it's very clear who is to blame.

83
00:08:44,000 --> 00:08:47,000
 It will just take me away, I guess.

84
00:08:47,000 --> 00:08:52,000
 But that has given us a level of control.

85
00:08:52,000 --> 00:08:56,000
 We have also accumulated a lot of foreign reserves.

86
00:08:56,000 --> 00:09:01,000
 We used the tourist boom to accumulate reserves, which are now about 35% of our GDP.

87
00:09:01,000 --> 00:09:10,000
 We have been using these reserves to manage the currency market, to keep it stable.

88
00:09:10,000 --> 00:09:16,000
 And there are very strict controls of how you can take one external debt.

89
00:09:16,000 --> 00:09:25,000
 Because in a small open economy, accumulating foreign debt can become an externality to others.

90
00:09:25,000 --> 00:09:35,000
 And also we limit also the use of FX futures, which are the main vehicles for carry trade or that.

91
00:09:35,000 --> 00:09:45,000
 Secondly, we enforce very high capital ratios of the banks, between 20-30%.

92
00:09:45,000 --> 00:09:48,000
 We have borrower-based measures.

93
00:09:48,000 --> 00:10:00,000
 You cannot get a mortgage in Iceland unless that you have, there is a 75%, you have 25% equity to being able to get a mortgage, for example.

94
00:10:00,000 --> 00:10:10,000
 And then very strict financial regulation.

95
00:10:10,000 --> 00:10:15,000
 And there are actually a couple of lessons I would like to take.

96
00:10:15,000 --> 00:10:44,000
 And so I see that the, essentially, that the American banking system is, there are, is in a, I think, in a kind of a systematic trouble, given that the banks there, they have, always when you implement a monetary tightening, there is a loss.

97
00:10:44,000 --> 00:10:45,000
 That is created.

98
00:10:45,000 --> 00:10:49,000
 It is just a question of who, who pairs the losses.

99
00:10:49,000 --> 00:11:07,000
 And so I am very clear that, given the bond holdings, or the US banking system, that, that the, the, um, um, equity ratios, or the market, or the market value of other equity is, is low or even zero.

100
00:11:07,000 --> 00:11:20,000
 And secondly, uh, as we've seen, there, there is a, um, lack of credibility, or, that the supervision is sufficiently, um, effective.

101
00:11:20,000 --> 00:11:35,000
 So I see, like, the, so-called systematic risk, um, exception, which, uh, which the, uh, which the, uh, which the, uh, has been, um, implemented, is basically, and in fact, a complete deposit guarantee.

102
00:11:35,000 --> 00:11:50,000
 And, uh, which I think that, um, cannot be basically abolished unless that there are done some structural changes in the, in the, um, in the American system.

103
